me|Danilo|N\u00fa\u00f1ez}}\n|[[Soles de Santo Domingo Este]]\n|5.2\n|\n|-\n|2017\n|{{flagicon|DOM}} {{sortname|Juan|Coronado}}\n|[[Reales de La Vega]]\n|6.5\n|\n|-\n|2018\n|{{flagicon|DOM}} {{sortname|Juan Miguel|Suero}}\n|[[Indios de San Francisco de Macor\u00eds]]\n|5.8\n|\n|-\n|2019\n|{{flagicon|DOM}} {{sortname|Adris|de Le\u00f3n}}\n|[[Metros de Santiago]]\n|5.5\n|<ref name=lnb19 />\n|}\n\n== References ==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20150102200347/http://www.lnb.com.do/home/ Official website]\n* [http://www.latinbasket.com/Dominica/basketball.asp Dominican league on Latinbasket.com] {{in lang|en}}\n* [https://twitter.com/lnbrd @LNBrd]\n\n{{Men's professional basketball leagues}}\n\n[[Category:Basketball in the Dominican Republic]]\n[[Category:Basketball leagues in the Caribbean|Dom]]\n\n{{DominicanRepublic-stub}}\n", "name_user": "Triple 8~enwiki", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eAssists:fix", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Liga_Nacional_de_Baloncesto"}
{"title_page": "Frank Spotnitz", "text_new": "<br />\n{{infobox person\n| name               = Frank Spotnitz\n| image              = Frank Spotnitz headshot 2015.jpg\n| caption            = Spotnitz in 2015\n| nationality        = American\n| birth_date         = \n| birth_place        = [[Camp Zama]], [[Japan]]\n| occupation         = Executive producer, showrunner, writer\n| alma_mater         = [[UCLA]] ([[Bachelor of Arts|BA]])<br/>[[American Film Institute]] ([[Master of Fine Arts|MFA]])\n}}\n\n'''Frank Charles Spotnitz''' (born November 11, 1960) is an award-winning<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://variety.com/2015/film/festivals/camerimage-honors-murch-spotnitz-menges-1201641073/|title=Camerimage Honors Murch, Powell, Stewart, Spotnitz, Menges|last=Wise|first=Damon|last2=Wise|first2=Damon|date=2015-11-15|website=Variety|language=en|access-date=2020-04-21}}</ref> American television writer and executive producer, best known for his work on ''[[The X-Files]]'' and ''[[The Man in the High Castle (TV series)|The Man in the High Castle]]''<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.denofgeek.com/tv/frank-spotnitz-interview-the-man-in-the-high-castle/|title=Frank Spotnitz interview: The Man In The High Castle|date=2015-11-19|website=Den of Geek|language=en-US|access-date=2020-04-21}}</ref>. Spotnitz is also the Chief Executive Officer and Founder of Big Light Productions, a London- and Paris-based production company, which specialises in international television series, including drama, comedy and documentaries. Spotnitz\u2019s 25+ career includes creating, writing and producing series with networks, cable, streaming and other broadcast platforms around the world.\n\nUnder the Big Light banner, Spotnitz has produced: Amazon\u2019s Emmy-winning ''[[The Man in the High Castle (TV series)|The Man in the High Castle]]''<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.biglight.com/high-castle-scores-nominations-at-the-68th-primetime-emmy-awards/|title=High Castle Scores Nominations at the 68th Primetime Emmy Awards \u2013 Big Light Productions|website=www.biglight.com|access-date=2020-04-21}}</ref>; ''[[Medici (TV series)|Medici]]: Masters of Florence'' and two seasons of ''[[Medici (TV series)|Medici]]: The Magnificent'' (RAI, Netflix, SFR Play)<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.denofgeek.com/tv/medici-season-2-frank-spotnitz-interview-the-real-history-is-too-graphic-even-for-television-to-show/|title=Medici season 2: Frank Spotnitz interview \u2018the real history is too graphic even for television to show\u2019|date=2019-01-24|website=Den of Geek|language=en-US|access-date=2020-04-21}}</ref>; ''[[The Indian Detective]]'' (Netflix, CTV); ''[[Ransom (TV series)|Ransom]]'' (CBS, Global, TF1, RTL)<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://variety.com/2016/tv/news/cbs-ransom-doubt-training-day-1201930190/|title=CBS Sets \u2018Ransom\u2019 for Saturdays, Schedules \u2018Doubt\u2019 and \u2018Training Day\u2019 Premieres|last=Holloway|first=Daniel|last2=Holloway|first2=Daniel|date=2016-11-30|website=Variety|language=en|access-date=2020-04-21}}</ref>; ''[[Crossing Lines]]'' season three with Tandem/StudioCanal; and ''[[Transporter: The Series|Transporter: The Serie]][[Transporter: The Series|s]]'' season two (TNT, M6, HBO Canada). Most recently, Spotnitz co-created and executive produced ''Leonardo'', which is currently in production in Italy<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://deadline.com/video/leonardo-aidan-turner-first-look/|title=First Look At Aidan Turner As Leonardo Da Vinci In Frank Spotnitz Series \u2018Leonardo\u2019|last=Kanter|first=Jake|last2=Kanter|first2=Jake|date=2020-04-15|website=Deadline|language=en|access-date=2020-04-21}}</ref>. \n==Early life and education==\nBorn in Camp Zama, Japan, in 1960, Spotnitz\u2019s father was a doctor in the US Army. Much of his childhood was peripatetic before the family settled in Phoenix, Arizona. \u00a0As a child, Spotnitz consumed television shows and films as much as he could, sometimes watching the same film two or three times in a row<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.frankspotnitz.com/about|title=Frank Spotnitz {{!}} About|website=Frank Spotnitz {{!}} Official|language=en-GB|access-date=2020-04-21}}</ref>. \n\nSpotnitz\u2019s education at Camelback High School inspired him to pursue a career in Hollywood.\n\nSpotnitz graduated from the [[University of California, Los Angeles]] (UCLA) with a bachelor's degree in English literature in 1982, where he was a reporter for the [[Daily Bruin]]. He later received a [[Master of Fine Arts|MFA]] in screenwriting from the [[AFI Conservatory]] in 1989.\n\n==Career==\n'''<big>Journalism</big>'''  \n\nUpon graduation, Spotnitz was employed as a wire-service reporter for the [[United Press International]] in Indianapolis and New York. He also briefly worked for the [[Associated Press]] in Paris. Spotnitz freelanced for ''[[Entertainment Weekly]]'' and''[[Rolling Stone]]'' before returning to his passion and studying screenwriting at [[American Film Institute|AFI]].  \n\n'''<big>Television</big>'''  \n\nSpotnitz created, executive produced and wrote several episodes of ''[[The Man in the High Castle (TV series)|The Man in the High Castle]]'', based on the classic alternative history novel by Philip K. Dick<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.denofgeek.com/tv/frank-spotnitz-talks-man-in-the-high-castle-phillip-k-dick/|title=Frank Spotnitz Talks Man in the High Castle, Phillip K. Dick|date=2015-11-19|website=Den of Geek|language=en-US|access-date=2020-04-21}}</ref>, which upon its release became Amazon\u2019s most viewed series ever<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://variety.com/2015/tv/news/the-man-in-the-high-castle-amazon-ratings-viewership-1201665925/|title=\u2018The Man in the High Castle\u2019 Becomes Amazon\u2019s Most-Streamed Original Series|last=Wagmeister|first=Elizabeth|last2=Wagmeister|first2=Elizabeth|date=2015-12-21|website=Variety|language=en|access-date=2020-04-21}}</ref>. Starring Alexa Davalos, Rufus Sewell and Joel de la Fuente, the series explores life in a 1962 America where the Allies lost the war and the country is divided between the fascist Japanese in the West and the Nazis in the East<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.kcrw.com/culture/shows/the-treatment/frank-spotnitz-amazons-the-man-in-the-high-castle|title=Frank Spotnitz: Amazon's 'The Man in the High Castle' {{!}} The Treatment|date=2015-12-01|website=KCRW|language=en|access-date=2020-04-21}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.kcrw.com/people/frank-spotnitz|title=Frank Spotnitz|website=KCRW|language=en|access-date=2020-04-21}}</ref>. The series won two Emmy Awards, was nominated for two others, and named Best Drama Series at the Roma Fiction Festival<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://tvshowpatrol.com/news/man-in-the-high-castle-wins-at-roma-fiction-fest/|title='Man in the High Castle' wins at Roma Fiction Fest|date=2015-11-16|website=TV Show Patrol|language=en-US|access-date=2020-04-21}}</ref>. It was also nominated for an ASC Award for Outstanding Cinematography, the USC Scripter Award and Best Drama at Monte Carlo Television Festival\u2019s Golden Nymph Awards<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.biglight.com/the-man-in-the-high-castle-named-one-of-2015s-best-shows/|title=The Man in the High Castle Named One of 2015\u2019s Best Shows \u2013 Big Light Productions|website=www.biglight.com|access-date=2020-04-21}}</ref>.   \n\nSpotnitz co-created, executive produced and co-wrote ''Leonardo'', currently in production<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.denofgeek.com/tv/leonardo-writing-underway-on-new-frank-spotnitz-drama/|title=Leonardo: writing underway on new Frank Spotnitz drama|date=2019-01-22|website=Den of Geek|language=en-US|access-date=2020-04-21}}</ref>. The eight-part limited series shows the terrible personal sacrifice that led ''Leonardo'' to create masterpieces that changed the way we see the world forever<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://variety.com/2018/tv/news/leonardo-tv-series-frank-spotnitz-steve-thompson-challenges-1203080970/|title=Frank Spotnitz and Steve Thompson on the Challenges Posed by Enigmatic \u2018Leonardo\u2019|last=Vivarelli|first=Nick|last2=Vivarelli|first2=Nick|date=2018-12-07|website=Variety|language=en|access-date=2020-04-21}}</ref>. Starring [[Aidan Turner]] and [[Freddie Highmore]], the series is the first produced by The Alliance (RAI, France T\u00e9l\u00e9vision, ZDF)<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://variety.com/2018/tv/news/frank-spotnitz-developing-leonardo-da-vinci-series-the-alliance-1202966792/|title=Frank Spotnitz Developing Series Depicting Leonardo da Vinci as Gay Outsider (EXCLUSIVE)|last=Vivarelli|first=Nick|last2=Vivarelli|first2=Nick|date=2018-10-03|website=Variety|language=en|access-date=2020-04-21}}</ref>.\n\nSpotnitz co-created, executive produced and co-wrote ''[[Medici (TV series)|Medici]]: Masters of Florence'', starring Richard Madden, Dustin Hoffman and Annabel Scholey<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://variety.com/2015/tv/global/game-of-thrones-richard-madden-dustin-hoffman-medici-masters-of-florence-1201601416/|title=Dustin Hoffman, Richard Madden to Star in TV Drama About Italy\u2019s Medici Family|last=Friedlander|first=Whitney|last2=Friedlander|first2=Whitney|date=2015-09-24|website=Variety|language=en|access-date=2020-04-21}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://variety.com/2016/tv/global/frank-spotnitz-on-why-medici-is-a-megahit-in-italy-u-k-u-s-deals-imminent-exclusive-1201919171/|title=Frank Spotnitz on Why \u2018Medici\u2019 Is a Megahit in Italy; U.K., U.S. Deals \u2018Imminent\u2019 (EXCLUSIVE)|last=Vivarelli|first=Nick|last2=Vivarelli|first2=Nick|date=2016-11-16|website=Variety|language=en|access-date=2020-04-21}}</ref>. Chronicling the rise of the Medici family during the Italian Renaissance, it shows how the family\u2019s ascent from simple merchants to power brokers sparked an economic and cultural revolution, creating powerful enemies in the process<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://variety.com/2016/tv/global/frank-spotnitz-medici-richard-madden-dustin-hoffman-1201744736-1201744736/|title=MipTV: Frank Spotnitz Talks \u2018Medici: Masters of Florence\u2019 With Dustin Hoffman, Richard Madden (EXCLUSIVE)|last=Hopewell|first=John|last2=Hopewell|first2=John|date=2016-04-04|website=Variety|language=en|access-date=2020-04-21}}</ref>. The Netflix Original Series was produced with Lux Vide Productions for RAI, Italy\u2019s largest broadcaster, and SFR in France<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://variety.com/2017/film/news/capri-film-festival-2016-winners-la-la-land-1201951042/|title=\u2018La La Land\u2019 Named Best Movie of the Year at Capri Hollywood Festival|last=Staff|first=Variety|last2=Staff|first2=Variety|date=2017-01-02|website=Variety|language=en|access-date=2020-04-21}}</ref>. The RAI premiere attracted a record-breaking seven million viewers in Italy, becoming the country\u2019s most-watched new series<ref>{{Cite news|last=France-Presse|first=Agence|url=https://www.theguardian.com/tv-and-radio/2016/apr/04/medici-drama-premiere-cannes-tv-festival-dustin-hoffman-renaissance|title=Dustin Hoffman to head up new Medici family TV drama|date=2016-04-04|work=The Guardian|access-date=2020-04-21|language=en-GB|issn=0261-3077}}</ref>. \n\nSet 20 years later, ''[[Medici (TV series)|Medici]]: The Magnificent'' starred Daniel Sharman, Bradley James and Sean Bean, and was also co-created, executive produced and co-written by Spotnitz<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://variety.com/2018/tv/global/first-look-at-netflix-medici-the-magnificent-1203093888/|title=First Look at Netflix\u2019s New Season of \u2018Medici\u2019: \u2018Blood Must Be Spilled\u2019|last=Clarke|first=Stewart|last2=Clarke|first2=Stewart|date=2018-12-20|website=Variety|language=en|access-date=2020-04-21}}</ref>. After an attempt on Piero de Medici\u2019s life, his son Lorenzo is forced to assume leadership of the family-run bank. Once in power, young Lorenzo resolves to abandon the cynical politics of the past to usher in a new era of creative and political revolution, bringing him into open conflict with rival banker Jacopo Pazzi, who will stop at nothing to defeat him. Their clash gives rise to one of the most thrilling true-life political intrigues of all time, the infamous Pazzi conspiracy. The second season of ''[[Medici (TV series)|Medici]]: The Magnificent'' was broadcast on RAI in December 2019 and premieres as a Netflix Original Series in May.\n\nIn 2017, Spotnitz co-created, executive produced and co-wrote the comedy-drama series ''[[The Indian Detective]]'' for Canadian broadcaster CTV and Netflix. It starred international comedy sensation Russell Peters, whom Forbes magazine ranked three times in its Top 10 highest-grossing comics list. Peters portrays Doug D\u2019Mello, a charming, smart Toronto cop, who unexpectedly finds himself investigating murder in his parents\u2019 Indian homeland, where, despite his heritage, he remains an outsider. Canada\u2019s biggest series debut in two years was the second-most watched programme on the day of its CTV premiere, with 1.6 million viewers. It was bestowed the Golden Screen Award by the Canadian Screen Academy.\n\n''[[Ransom (TV series)|Ransom]]'', produced for CBS in the US, France\u2019s TF1, Canada\u2019s Corus/Global and RTL in Germany, was a suspense drama set against an international backdrop<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://thepcprinciple.com/?p=11897|title=Interview: Frank Spotnitz|last=DigitalCavalry|date=2018-05-21|website=The PC Principle|language=english|access-date=2020-04-21}}</ref>. It starred [[Luke Roberts (actor)|Luke Roberts]] and was co-created, executive produced and co-written by Spotnitz<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.c21media.net/eone-delivers-ransom-around-world/|title=eOne delivers Ransom around world|website=C21media|language=en-us|access-date=2020-04-21}}</ref>. The thriller follows crisis and hostage negotiator Eric Beaumont, whose team is brought in to save lives when no one else can. Beaumont understands criminals better than they understand themselves and uses his insight into human behaviour to resolve the most difficult kidnap and ransom cases. Despite the stakes, Beaumont refuses to resort to violence, even when confronted by some of the world\u2019s most dangerous criminals. ''Ransom'' was VOX Germany\u2019s highest rated drama premiere for over 15 months and France\u2019s TF1 premiere reached over 4 million viewers for a market share of 25%. The show ran for three seasons<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://deadline.com/2018/07/ransom-renewed-third-season-global-frank-spotnitz-luke-roberts-1202427218/|title=\u2018Ransom\u2019 Renewed For Season 3 By Global & CBS|last=Petski|first=Denise|last2=Petski|first2=Denise|date=2018-07-16|website=Deadline|language=en|access-date=2020-04-21}}</ref>.\n\nIn 2012, Spotnitz created, wrote and executive produced the international spy drama series ''[[Hunted (2012 TV series)|Hunted]]'' for BBC1 and HBO/Cinemax, starring [[Melissa George]], [[Adam Rayner]], [[Stephen Dillane]] and [[Patrick Malahide]]<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.denofgeek.com/tv/frank-spotnitz-interview-hunted-the-bbc-cancellation-the-x-files-and-more/|title=Frank Spotnitz interview: Hunted, the BBC cancellation, The X-Files, and more...|date=2012-12-08|website=Den of Geek|language=en-US|access-date=2020-04-21}}</ref>. \u00a0The series follows Sam Hunter, an operative for a private spy agency, Byzantium. After she is betrayed and nearly killed by one of her colleagues, Sam returns to London in an attempt to root out the traitor, while working undercover in the home of a wealthy and dangerous London gangster on an assignment that could cost her life. The series was BAFTA nominated for cinematography and won the ASC Award. It was also nominated for Best Editing by the Royal Television Society.\n\nSpotnitz served on ''[[The X-Files]]'' for eight of its nine seasons after joining the show in 1994<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://play.acast.com/s/thexcast/51fbfecedad2464d9da852180d42d686|title=284. Interview: Frank Spotnitz (Producer of The X-Files)|website=acast|language=en|access-date=2020-04-21}}</ref>. He called it \u201ca life-changing experience\u201d, graduating from staff writer to executive producer after three seasons. He directed two episodes and wrote or co-wrote more than 40 instalments of the series, including the Emmy-nominated \u201cMemento Mori\u201d with [[Chris Carter (screenwriter)|Chris Carter]],[[Vince Gilligan]] and [[John Shiban]] in 1997. He served for four years as executive producer and three years as president of Carter\u2019s Ten Thirteen Productions. He was a producer and co-writer of both ''[[The X-Files]]'' feature files, ''[[The X-Files (film)|Fight the Future]]''(1998) and ''[[The X-Files: I Want to Believe|I Want to Believe]]'' (2008). Spotnitz shares three Golden Globes for Best Dramatic Series and a Peabody Award for his work on ''[[The X-Files]]''. He was also nominated for an Emmy Award for writing and three times for Outstanding Drama Series.\n\nSpotnitz\u2019s additional writing and producing credits include: counter-terrorism drama series ''[[Strike Back (TV series)|Strike Back]]'' (HBO/Cinemax, Sky); action series ''[[Transporter: The Series]]'' (TNT); ABC\u2019s mystery series ''[[Night Stalker (TV series)|Night Stalker]]'' (ABC), starring Stuart Townsend and Gabrielle Union; Michael Mann\u2019s crime series ''[[Robbery Homicide Division]]'' (CBS); unconventional heroes comedy-drama ''[[The Lone Gunmen (TV series)|The Lone Gunmen]]'' (Fox); sci-fi drama ''[[Harsh Realm]]'' (Fox); and crime thriller ''[[Millennium (TV series)|Millennium]]'' (Fox).\n\n== Writing process ==\nSpotnitz adopted the writers\u2019 room process from his experience in the US, which he brought to the UK when he founded Big Light Productions. He cards the story scene by scene on a corkboard, with one board for each episode. \u00a0Spotnitz favours carding in order to better analyse the story and to enable better collaboration<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://tbivision.com/2019/12/13/leonardo-creator-frank-spotnitz-urges-creative-freedom-and-co-operation/|title=\u2018Leonardo\u2019 creator Frank Spotnitz urges creative freedom and co-operation|date=2019-12-13|website=TBI Vision|language=en-US|access-date=2020-04-21}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://tbivision.com/2019/12/13/leonardo-creator-frank-spotnitz-urges-creative-freedom-and-co-operation/|title=\u2018Leonardo\u2019 creator Frank Spotnitz urges creative freedom and co-operation|date=2019-12-13|website=TBI Vision|language=en-US|access-date=2020-04-21}}</ref>. He always asks: why do I care about this story? Why do I care about this character? And aims to draw in the audience early on.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/writersroom/writers-lab/be-inspired/frank-spotnitz|title=BBC - Frank Spotnitz - Writers Room|website=www.bbc.co.uk|access-date=2020-04-21}}</ref>\n\n== Personal life ==\nSpotnitz lives with his family in Paris and divides his time between Big Light\u2019s London and Paris offices<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.allocine.fr/personne/fichepersonne_gen_cpersonne=71765.html|title=Frank Spotnitz|last=AlloCine|website=AlloCin\u00e9|access-date=2020-04-21}}</ref>.\n\n== Works and publications ==\n'''<big>Books</big>''' \n\n''TV Outside the Box: Trailblazing in the Digital Television Revolution'', Neil Landau (2015)\n\n'''<big>Filmography</big>'''\n\n*[[Leonardo (TV series 2020)|Leonardo]] (2020)\n*[[Medici (TV series)|Medici]] (2016\u20132019)\n*[[Ransom (TV series)|Ransom]] (2017\u20132019)\n*[[The Indian Detective]] (2017)\n*[[The Man in the High Castle (TV series)|The Man in the High Castle]] (2015\u20132019)\n*[[Crossing Lines]] (2015)\n*[[Transporter: The Series]] (2014)\n*[[Hunted (2015 TV series)|Hunted]] (2012)\n*[[Strike Back: Project Dawn]] (2011)\n*[[Samurai Girl (miniseries)|Samurai Girl]] (2008)\n*[[The X-Files: I Want to Believe]] (2008)\n*[[A.M.P.E.D.]] (2007)\n*[[Night Stalker (TV series)|Night Stalker]] (2005\u20132006)\n*[[Robbery Homicide Division]] (2002\u20132003)\n*[[The Lone Gunmen (TV series)|The Lone Gunmen]] (2001)\n*[[Harsh Realm]] (1999)\n*[[The X-Files (film)|The X-Files: Fight the Future]] (1998)\n*Inside the X-Files (1998)\n*[[The X-Files]] (1996\u20132002)\n*[[Millennium (TV series)|Millennium]] (1996)\n\n\n'''<big>The X-Files credits</big>'''\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n!<abbr>No.</abbr>overall\n!No. of season\n!<abbr>No.</abbr> in\nseason\n!Title\n!Directed by\n!Written by\n!Original air date\n!<abbr>Prod.</abbr>code\u200a\n!US viewers\n(millions)\n|-\n! rowspan=\"1\" |41\n|2\n|17\n|\"[[End Game (The X-Files)|End Game]]\"\n|Rob Bowman\n|[[Frank Spotnitz]]\n|February 17, 1995\n|2X17\n|17.5\n|-\n! rowspan=\"1\" |48\n|2\n|24\n|\"[[Our Town (The X-Files)|Our Town]]\"\n|Rob Bowman\n|Frank Spotnitz\n|May 12, 1995\n|2X24\n|14.5\n|-\n! rowspan=\"1\" |58\n|3\n|9\n|\"[[Nisei (The X-Files)|Nisei]]\"\n|David Nutter\n|Chris Carter & Howard Gordon & [[Frank Spotnitz]]\n|November 24, 1995\n|3X09\n|16.36\n|-\n! rowspan=\"1\" |59\n|3\n|10\n|\"[[731 (The X-Files)|731]]\"\n|Rob Bowman\n|Frank Spotnitz\n|December 1, 1995\n|3X10\n|17.68\n|-\n! rowspan=\"1\" |64\n|3\n|15\n|\"[[Piper Maru]]\"\n|Rob Bowman\n|Frank Spotnitz & Chris Carter\n|February 9, 1996\n|3X15\n|16.44\n|-\n! rowspan=\"1\" |65\n|3\n|16\n|\"[[Apocrypha (The X-Files)|Apocrypha]]\"\n|Kim Manners\n|Frank Spotnitz & Chris Carter\n|February 16, 1996\n|3X16\n|16.71\n|-\n! rowspan=\"1\" |81\n|4\n|8\n|\"[[Tunguska (The X-Files)|Tunguska]]\"\n|Kim Manners\n|[[Frank Spotnitz]] & Chris Carter\n|November 24, 1996\n|4X09\n|18.85\n|-\n! rowspan=\"1\" |82\n|4\n|9\n|\"[[Terma (The X-Files)|Terma]]\"\n|Rob Bowman\n|Frank Spotnitz & Chris Carter\n|December 1, 1996\n|4X10\n|17.34\n|-\n! rowspan=\"1\" |85\n|4\n|12\n|\"[[Leonard Betts]]\"\n|Kim Manners\n|Vince Gilligan & John Shiban & Frank Spotnitz\n|January 26, 1997\n|4X14\n|29.15\n|-\n! rowspan=\"1\" |87\n|4\n|14\n|\"[[Memento Mori (The X-Files)|Memento Mori]]\"\n|Rob Bowman\n|Chris Carter & Vince Gilligan & John Shiban & Frank Spotnitz\n|February 9, 1997\n|4X15\n|19.10\n|-\n